627  // BFS data structures
628  set <Node*> visited;
629  queue <Node*> g1_nodes;
630  queue <Node*> g2_nodes;
631 
632  // Initialize BFS
633  g1_nodes.push(g1->getRoot());
634  g2_nodes.push(g2->getRoot());
635  visited.insert(g1->getRoot());
636 
637  Node *t1; // use these temp pointers as opposed to the graph's "current" pointer in order
638  Node *t2; // to not change the value of the current pointer, which may be in use by another function
639 
640  // Main BFS Loop
641  while (!g1_nodes.empty()) {
642  // Pop next nodes from queue
643  t1 = g1_nodes.front(); g1_nodes.pop();
644  t2 = g2_nodes.front(); g2_nodes.pop();
645 
646  // Check equality of both the left and right predecessors
647  Node *g1_pred;
648  Node *g2_pred;
649  for (int predecessor_number = 0; predecessor_number < 2; ++predecessor_number) {
650  if (predecessor_number == 0) { // left predecessor
651  g1_pred = t1->p1;
652  g2_pred = t2->p1;
653  }
654  else { // right predecessor
655  g1_pred = t1->p2;
656  g2_pred = t2->p2;
657  }
658  if (g1_pred->is_op) { // If the predecessor is an operation
659  if (!(g2_pred)) return false; // g1->current->p1 exists. but not g2->current->p1
660  if ( (g1_pred->I) != (g2_pred->I) ) return false; // both exist, but node doesn't match
661  if ( visited.find(g1_pred) == visited.end() ) {
662  g1_nodes.push(g1_pred);
663  g2_nodes.push(g2_pred);
664  visited.insert(g1_pred);
665  }
666  }
667  else if (g2_pred->is_op) return false; // g2->current->p1 exists. but not g1->current->p1
668  }
669  }
670  return true;
671 }

435  bool IllegalFanouts = false;
436 
437  Value::use_iterator uit = pred->use_begin();
438  Value::use_iterator end = pred->use_end();
439  for ( ; uit != end; ++uit) {
440  Instruction * successor = dyn_cast<Instruction> ( *uit );
441  if (!successor) continue; // successor is not an instruction
442  // if the successor is in the same state
443  if ( fsm->getEndState(successor) == fsm->getEndState(pred) ) {
444  // and if the graph does not contain the successor
445  if ( g->GraphNodes.find(successor) == g->GraphNodes.end() ) {
446  IllegalFanouts = true;
447  break;
448  }
449  }
450  }
451  if (IllegalFanouts) return false;
452  return true;
453 }

bool legup::is_inst_a_mc_path_src_or_dest ( Instruction *  i)

Definition at line 68 of file MultiCycle.cpp.

68  {
69  // This function determines whether the given instruction acts as the source
70  // or destination of a multi-cycle path. Many instructions will simply be
71  // chained as part of the MC path, but some instructions cannot be chained
72  // and therefore will start or terminate the path ("source" or
73  // "destination").
74  // Destinations are AKA sinks or roots. These source or dest instructions
75  // will
76  // not have their output registers removed, but rather their registers will
77  // stay
78  // and act as the source/dest of the MC path. So these source/dest
79  // instructions
80  // are equivalently "registered instructions" (after all other instructions
81  // have
82  // had their registers removed to enable MC / de-pipelined paths).
83  //
84  // Note that in most cases there is no distinction between sources or
85  // destinations of MC paths, because if an instruction terminated one
86  // MC path then it is also the beginning of the next one (except e.g. for
87  // store instructions which are only dests).
88  //
89  // The instructions which are src/dsts of MC paths, i.e. whose registers
90  // persist
91  // even after de-pipelining of data paths, are:
92  //
93  // - Instructions used across BB, including PHIs (for now)
94  // - call instructions: there are registers before module input
95  // ports (so the register is "outside the function")
96  // - Return instructions
97  // - Loads (registers are either memory_controller_out_reg_a or b)
98  // - Stores do NOT have registers (no input reg to LegUp altsyncrams)
99  // but still terminate data paths
100  // - Instructions with latency > 0
101  //
102  // Handle any more types as they come up (e.g. other terminators)
103 
104  bool is_mc_src_or_dest = false;
105 
106  // Loads and stores
107  if (isMem(i)) {
108  is_mc_src_or_dest = true;
109  }
110  // Instructions with latency
111  // Note: we need to be careful with instructions that are pipelined
112  // because pipelined instructions can't be sources of MC paths (new value
113  // each cycle) unless we guarantee that there won't be new data during the
114  // multi-cycle duration. So for now I'll add instructions with latency > 0
115  // but exclude dividers and remainders, since they cannot be MC sources
116  // (although maybe their inputs can come from MC paths?)
117  /*
118  else if (Scheduler::getNumInstructionCycles(i) > 0 && !isDiv(i) &&
119  !isRem(i)) {
120  is_mc_src_or_dest = true;
121  }
122  */
123  // PHI instructions
124  else if (isa<PHINode>(*i)) {
125  is_mc_src_or_dest = true;
126  }
127  // Instructions used across BB
128  else if (has_uses_in_other_BB(i)) {
129  is_mc_src_or_dest = true;
130  }
131  // Call instructions
132  else if (isa<CallInst>(*i)) {
133  is_mc_src_or_dest = true;
134  }
135  // Ret instructions
136  else if (isa<ReturnInst>(*i)) {
137  is_mc_src_or_dest = true;
138  }
139 
140  return is_mc_src_or_dest;
141 }

243  // can be "used", instead of ones with bodies.
244  std::vector<Function*> NewFunctions;
245 
246  Function *Last = --M.end(); // Figure out where the last real fn is.
247 
248  for (Module::iterator I = M.begin(); ; ++I) {
249  if (std::find(Named.begin(), Named.end(), &*I) == Named.end()) {
250  Function *New = Function::Create(I->getFunctionType(),
251  GlobalValue::ExternalLinkage);
252  New->copyAttributesFrom(I);
253 
254  // If it's not the named function, delete the body of the function
255  I->dropAllReferences();
256 
257  M.getFunctionList().push_back(New);
258  NewFunctions.push_back(New);
259  New->takeName(I);
260  }
261 
262  if (&*I == Last) break; // Stop after processing the last function
263  }
264 
265  // Now that we have replacements all set up, loop through the module,
266  // deleting the old functions, replacing them with the newly created
267  // functions.
268  if (!NewFunctions.empty()) {
269  unsigned FuncNum = 0;
270  Module::iterator I = M.begin();
271  do {
272  if (std::find(Named.begin(), Named.end(), &*I) == Named.end()) {
273  // Make everything that uses the old function use the new dummy fn
274  I->replaceAllUsesWith(NewFunctions[FuncNum++]);
275 
276  Function *Old = I;
277  ++I; // Move the iterator to the new function
278 
279  // Delete the old function!
280  M.getFunctionList().erase(Old);
281 
282  } else {
283  ++I; // Skip the function we are extracting
284  }
285  } while (&*I != NewFunctions[0]);
286  }
287

289  set_all_linkage(M, GlobalValue::ExternalLinkage);

Definition at line 143 of file MultiCycle.cpp.

143  {
144  // This function determines whether the given instruction can be pushed to a
145  // later state. We do this in the multi-cycle flow, after the first
146  // scheduling.
147  // Data paths are de-pipelined and the remaining instructions with registers
148  // are the sources and roots of multi-cycle paths. We can then extend the
149  // latency of MC paths by pushing these MC path root / destination
150  // instructions
151  // to later states.
152  //
153  // Note: See comments below. Ideally, this function is not needed, and
154  // "is_inst_a_mc_path_src_or_dest()" should be called instead. But there
155  // are some exceptions where instructions that are destinations of MC paths
156  // actually shouldn't have their latencies extended (e.g. PHIs).
157 
158  bool can_push_to_later_state = false;
159 
160  // Loads and stores
161  // if (isMem(i)) {
162  if (isa<StoreInst>(*i)) {
163  // Note that in general we want to push instructions to an exact later
164  // state, e.g. their current state + 1. But for loads and stores we
165  // need to relax the constraint to any state >= current state + 1,
166  // due to resource constraints (only 2 scheduled per state.)
167  // Also, it might seem that loads are only sources of MC data paths
168  // and never dests, but the address port of a load can have some
169  // logic (getelementptr) so they can be dests as well.
170  // For now, don't push loads, although some paths may benefit from
171  // pushing.
172  can_push_to_later_state = true;
173  }
174  /*
175  // Instructions with latency
176  else if (Scheduler::getNumInstructionCycles(i) > 0) {
177  // See comment in is_inst_a_mc_path_src_or_dest()
178  if (!isRem(i) && !isDiv(i)) {
179  can_push_to_later_state = true;
180  }
181  }
182  */
183  // PHI instructions
184  else if (isa<PHINode>(*i)) {
185 
186  // PHIs often terminate MC paths but they are not re-scheduled
187  // because they should always be at the start of their BB
188  // (i.e. don't push PHIs to a later state)
189  // In the future however PHIs don't need to have registers, they
190  // can simply be muxes
191 
192  }
193  // Instructions used across BB
194  else if (has_uses_in_other_BB(i)) {
195  can_push_to_later_state = true;
196  }
197  // Call instructions
198  else if (isa<CallInst>(*i)) {
199  can_push_to_later_state = true;
200  }
201  /*
202  // Note: pushing branches/returns is how to increase the latency
203  // of the BB. I used to do this for every infrequent BB but now
204  // I only do it if the BB has a MC path, since some BB are short
205  // (e.g. 1 cycle), so it doesn't make sense to extend it e.g. from
206  // 1 to 2 cycles if there aren't even any MC paths in it.
207 
208  // Ret instructions
209  else if (isa<ReturnInst>(*i)) {
210  //can_push_to_later_state = true;
211  }
212 
213  // Branch instructions
214  else if (isa<BranchInst>(*i)) {
215  //can_push_to_later_state = true;
216  }
217  else if (isa<SwitchInst>(*i)) {
218  //can_push_to_later_state = true;
219  }
220  */
221 
222  return can_push_to_later_state;
223 }

)

setStateTransitions - determine the state transitions given a terminating instruction

Definition at line 327 of file SchedulerDAG.cpp.

329  {
330 
331  lastState->setTerminating(true);
332 
333  // unreachable could occur in a basic block like:
334  // bb: ; preds = %entry
335  // %2 = tail call i32 (i8*, ...)* @printf(i8* noalias getelementptr
336  // inbounds ([32 x i8]* @.str1, i32 0, i32 0)) nounwind ; <i32> [#uses=0]
337  // tail call void @exit(i32 1) noreturn nounwind
338  // unreachable
339  if (isa<UnreachableInst>(TI) || TI->getOpcode() == Instruction::Ret) {
340  lastState->setDefaultTransition(waitState);
341  return;
342  }
343 
344  lastState->setTransitionVariable(TI->getOperand(0));
345 
346  BasicBlock *Default;
347  if (const SwitchInst *SI = dyn_cast<SwitchInst>(TI)) {
348 
349  for (unsigned i = 2, e = SI->getNumOperands(); i != e; i += 2) {
350  Value *value = SI->getOperand(i);
351  assert(value);
352  BasicBlock *Succ = dyn_cast<BasicBlock>(SI->getOperand(i + 1));
353  State *state = bbFirstState[Succ];
354 
355  lastState->addTransition(state, value);
356  }
357 
358  Default = dyn_cast<BasicBlock>(SI->getDefaultDest());
359 
360  } else if (const BranchInst *B = dyn_cast<BranchInst>(TI)) {
361 
362  if (B->isConditional()) {
363  Default = dyn_cast<BasicBlock>(TI->getSuccessor(1));
364 
365  BasicBlock *Succ = dyn_cast<BasicBlock>(B->getSuccessor(0));
366  State *state = bbFirstState[Succ];
367 
368  lastState->addTransition(state);
369  } else {
370  Default = dyn_cast<BasicBlock>(TI->getSuccessor(0));
371  }
372 
373  } else {
374  llvm_unreachable(0);
375  }
376 
377  State *state = bbFirstState[Default];
378  lastState->setDefaultTransition(state);
379 }
